-- South Korean Stocks Rebound From Yesterday's Selloff, Kospi Advances 2.2%
-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 2010-11-12T00:07:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-12/south-korean-stocks-rebound-from-yesterday-s-selloff-kospi-advances-2-2-.html
South Korean stocks rebounded after
a selloff in the final minutes of trading yesterday sent the
benchmark Kospi Index to its biggest drop in more than five
months.  Samsung Electronics Co., Asia’s biggest maker of chips,
flat screens and mobile phones, climbed 2.5 percent, and Hyundai
Motor Co., South Korea’s largest automaker, gained 2.8 percent.
The stocks contributed the most to the Kospi’s 2.7 percent drop
yesterday that erased about $26 billion of market value.  The benchmark Kospi stock index rose 2.2 percent to
1,957.60 as of 9:03 a.m. on the Korea Exchange today.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Allen Wan at 
